transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Hi, thank you for calling Viagra at Score Blue. How can I help you today?

Speaker 2: Yes, you all keep trying to send me some more while you keep trying to tap my credit card, and I need to cancel that.

Speaker 1: That was supposed to be a one-time deal to try it out, and I never signed up for no prescription or nothing.

Speaker 2: Okay, well, let me look at your prescription, and we'll see how it was organized. Can I get your full name and date of birth, please?

Speaker 1: It's Bradley Weber. Date of birth is February 9, 1962.

Speaker 2: Okay, so, Bradley, what I'm seeing here is the doctor wrote your prescription back in September, and this is for a quantity of 50 of the 50-milligram Viagra. Is that accurate?

Speaker 1: That's correct.

Speaker 2: Okay, it looks like the doctor wrote it with refills, so what happened right here, based on the doctor's schedule recommendations, it attempted to go through.

Speaker 1: Now, you are not charged anything. Nothing has been shipped out, okay?

Speaker 2: No, I've had it blocked on this end, but I keep trying. I mean, I've said it time and time again, and there's another attempt on it.

Speaker 1: Okay, well, it's just, you know, this is perfectly adjustable. This is not a subscription. You're not required to get this monthly or bimonthly, or in this case, every three months.

Speaker 2: If you wanted, you could pause this, all right, so this would not be automatically deducted from your account, and you could just simply call in and place orders as needed.

Speaker 1: Okay, yeah, I can live with that, but I don't want anything sent regularly.

Speaker 2: Sure, exactly, so the next time you want a refill, just feel free to give us a call.

Speaker 1: Okay, that's what I will do, but y'all will stop tapping my card, please?

Speaker 2: Correct, yes, sir, that's not going to happen.

Speaker 1: Okay, all right, thank you.

Speaker 2: Yep, thank you.

Speaker 1: Bye.
